      <format>text/x-wiki</format>
      <text bytes="17522" xml:space="preserve">[[File:Mercury, Venus and the Moon Align.jpg|thumb|300px|A conjunction of [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] and [[Venus]] appears above the [[Moon]], as viewed from the [[Paranal Observatory]] in northern [[Chile]].]]
In [[astronomy]], a '''conjunction''' occurs when two [[astronomical object]]s or [[spacecraft]] have either the same [[right ascension]] or the same [[ecliptic coordinate system|ecliptic longitude]], usually as observed from Earth.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
 | url=http://asa.hmnao.com/AsA/SecM/Glossary.html#conjunction
 | title=Conjunction
 | work=Glossary, The Astronomical Almanac Online
 | author=Her Majesty's Nautical Almanac Office and United States Naval Observatory
 | year=2012
 | accessdate=2012-07-08
 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615043850/http://asa.hmnao.com/AsA/SecM/Glossary.html#conjunction
 | archive-date=2013-06-15
 | url-status=dead
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book 
 | title=Astronomical Algorithms 
 | author=Jean Meeus
 | publisher=Willman-Bell Inc., Richmond, Virginia
 | year=1991
}}&lt;/ref&gt;
The [[astronomical symbol]] for conjunction is ☌ (in [[Unicode]] U+260C) and handwritten [[File:Astronomical conjunction symbol.png|20px]]. 
The conjunction symbol is not used in modern astronomy. It continues to be used in [[Astrological symbols#Aspects|astrology]].{{citation needed (lead)|date=March 2019}}

When two objects always appear close to the [[ecliptic]]—such as two [[planet]]s, the [[Moon]] and a planet, or the [[Sun]] and a planet—this fact implies an apparent close approach between the objects as seen on the sky. A related word, ''[[appulse]]'', is the minimum apparent separation on the sky of two astronomical objects.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
 | url=http://asa.hmnao.com/AsA/SecM/Glossary.html#appulse
 | title=Appulse
 | work=Glossary, The Astronomical Almanac Online
 | author=Her Majesty's Nautical Almanac Office and United States Naval Observatory
 | year=2012
